                    <h5 class="card-title tit-design"><b>2. Cut back on social media</b></h5>
                    <p class="card-text content">
                        “Constantly consuming information about other people’s lives may cause someone to compare themselves and promote feelings of low self-worth, which increases feelings of anxiety and depression,” says Adeeyo.
                        To spend less time on social media, try to:
                    </p>
                    <ol class="content">
                        <li>keep your phone in a drawer or outside your bedroom while sleeping.</li>
                        <li>make a list of alternate, more meaningful activities to replace your usual scrolling sessions.</li>
                        <li>turn off notifications or delete social apps from your phone.</li>
                    </ol>
                    <p class="card-text content">
                        Talking to someone you trust – whether a friend, a family member, or a colleague – can help. You may feel better if you are able to openly share what you are going through with someone who cares about you. If you live in an area where face-to-face interactions are limited, you can still stay connected with your loved ones through a video call, phone call or messaging app.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
